metadata.name: Unbalanced Life #21
metadata.description:
Most of the time we don't know what we do with our lives, we try hard and make decisions hoping for the best. We could go from a balanced and well-directed life to a disastrous and shattered one.

"Unbalanced Life" is an abstraction of these aspects. Each line represents a stage in your life. Over each line are "life decisions" that you take. Several are well defined, others are just a mess and explode, like in real life! 

The life type will be included below in the right corner unless your life is seriously "Shattered", then the name will be huge enough to punch you right in the face, or you could get "No Life" and with that, a disappointing tag will remember you that at less your life is better than this NFT.

What kind of life will you get?

You will face these challenging features:

Life types
- Shattered life
- Unbalanced life
- Balanced life
- Wasted life
- Lack of life
- No life 

Four color schemes
- Groovy seventies
- Rad 80's
- Fire and fury
- Outstanding carbon

Well-thought decisions
- Boolean

metadata.name: Anfractuous #53
metadata.description: The title is quite literally a visual description of the work, as anfractuous means: characterized by windings and turnings; sinuous; circuitous. With this project I aimed to strike a balance between easily recognizable smooth large scale forms and the small fragmented details that populate these forms.

metadata.name: Limits of Infinite Space #27
metadata.description:
In this work, infinite growth becomes a visual metaphor illustrating how space expands infinitely within defined boundaries. Similar to the mathematical concept where the limit of a function can be equal to 1 as "x" tends to infinity, one can observe how infinite expansion comes to a halt at a boundary represented by the thick straight line in the middle of this artistic creation.

As this expansion continues, something astonishing happens: space emerges and materializes. The concentric shapes stretching into infinity create layers upon layers of space that, even though arising from a seemingly endless process, define and delineate clear areas within the canvas. This duality between unlimited growth and the creation of space reveals the beauty and paradox of how even in the pursuit of the infinite, defined spaces can be found within the confines of the finite.

metadata.name: ProcGen Entomology #341
metadata.description:
Realtime 3D in-browser procedural generation of insect-like models, with a look reminiscent of vintage entomology illustrations.

The project is about the fact that insects are cool first and foremost.
This is also about nostalgia.

Everything is procedural except for the font. The exposed features only describe the most visible parts.

I wrote mord words, about where it came from, and some technical details on the procedural aspect at:
https://ulucode.com/projects/entomology/

GPU Required!

Interface : 
Space : show/hide menu
Mouse Left : Rotate
Mouse Right : Pan
Mouse Middle/Wheel : Zoom

Captures only work in Live mode.

metadata.name: illusions #42
metadata.description:
"illusions" is an experiment with textures made from grains, flows and noise, which slowly forms into an abstract figure. 
It can resemble clouds, nebulae, waterfalls, neon bars and anything else your brain can imagine while looking at it.

The growth and formation patterns of "illusions" are 3:
They can grow in the form of a cloud, in the form of lines/squares or just a noise, and also in a glitch effect.

There are 11 color palettes and one of them is monochromatic in black/white, it is the rarest as there is only 4% chance of happening.

You can open the live view to have a better experience.
-Also in live view you can press the "s" key to save a .png file of the artwork.

Works properly on Chrome.

This is an artwork in p5.js.



Omar Lobato Neto, 10/03/2022

metadata.name: Zero-player game #54
metadata.description:
The pattern is endless and doesn't loop. It is deterministic: even if you scroll a mile away and then return, you will find each pixel exactly where it was. Give it a try!

When I was young, It was intimidating to think about space because it was endless. I felt like I'm completely dissolving in it and turning into zero.

I was getting older and exploring the world around me. What seemed large and complex turned out to be the result of the interaction of simple elements. Even the infinite Universe can be decomposed and understood.

“Zero-player game” is a cellular automaton through which I explore the concept of infinity and emergence. The game starts with a surface covered by random cells. Over six iterations the image becomes more complex as the cells divide and change their colors according to a set of thirty two rules.

More information about the project at https://ivandianov.com/zero-player-game/

- Swipe or use arrow keys to navigate.
- Add ?lat=100500&lon=100500 to URL and teleport to a distant location.
- Press “S” to save a picture.

metadata.name: origins 2 #81
metadata.description: I have always been fascinated by long exposure photography and the ghostly figures that can be created through doing so. This is a continuation of my original "origins" piece but with rotating and pulsing animations.

metadata.name: Bedlam #69
metadata.description:
Originally a study of paint brushes and texture, this project morphed. I started to find a medley of painting with the texture of handmade rugs, leveraging this medium to not just recreate the everyday, but let my imagination run. 

Enjoy each abstract piece that "Bedlam" has to offer, with 25 palettes, 5 brush styles, and an endless combination of stroke lengths and layering effects, there is much to be discovered.

It can take up to a minute for the Painting to finish, depending on your hardware.

Press 's' in Live View to save a png.

metadata.name: ORBIS #24
metadata.description:
Generative algorithm creating a beautiful chaos of random size and color squares and circles inside a rotated matrix. 

14 different color palettes 
3 sizes 

made with p5.js

metadata.name: Insula #154
metadata.description:
An audiovisual collection.
.
Click to start the sound.
..
Insula is an endless generative music player.
...
There are 6 different grid size; 4 squares and 20 squares are the rare ones.

2 different background texture; Lines, Grain.

2 different color placement; Circular, Linear.

7 different noise types.

8 different scales with fixed root notes; C Maj., C Lydian, D Dorian, D Min. Penta., G Maj., G Maj. Penta., F Mixolydian, F Min.

2 different rhythmical structures; 2:3, 4:5.

2 different note indicator style; Circle and Square. Square is rare and behaves differently.

5 different note indicator line divisions.
....
Harmonization process based on Avro Part's 'Tintinnabuli' style.

Grid design inspired from Novation's Launchpad.


Made with p5.js and Web Audio.

Ilgın İçözü, December 2021
@distcollective

metadata.name: NATURAL 03 #98
metadata.description:
NATURAL 03 are generative and animated pieces creating a visual based on a noise with a painting effect.
 It’s the third part of a collection called NATURAL.
The size, position and frequency of trails are generated for each token, along with the color theme.  Movements are generated by a flow based on a noise, it's different for each views.

You can press spacebar to stop the animation. 
Save a png : open live and `cmd/ctrl + s` 

 Features :
	- Generated grid between 20 and 60 cols and rows
	- 2 kind of shapes (circles and squares), it can be full of squares or circles 👀
	- The shapes can be stroked or filled : sometimes it can be full stroked or filled 👀
	- Duration between 18 and 24s
	- Background color :  color randomly get from 1 of 134 color themes

Created by Quentin Hocdé, in Brussels (Belgium).

metadata.name: MOSAIQUE #72

Restless tiles moving together, striving for the perfect arrangement.

Features:
6 Color palettes
5 Movement classes
4 Board sizes
6 Tile count variations
10 Intervals

Rendered with regl in WebGL and gl.POINTS.

metadata.name: Gestalt #882
metadata.description:
"Gestalt" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022

A flurry of many elements derived from my past (and future) strewn across a single canvas. As random as things seem, collectively time tends to reveal hints of order in the chaos. Sometimes, more is more.

Controls:
• Left-click/tap reassembles the piece with one less element each time
• 'R' reassembles the piece with all elements
• 'S' saves the output

“𝚃𝚑𝚎 𝚠𝚑𝚘𝚕𝚎 𝚒𝚜 𝚐𝚛𝚎𝚊𝚝𝚎𝚛 𝚝𝚑𝚊𝚗 𝚝𝚑𝚎 𝚜𝚞𝚖 𝚘𝚏 𝚒𝚝𝚜 𝚙𝚊𝚛𝚝𝚜.”
